{"title": "Asian Insider: Vietnam flexes \u2018bamboo diplomacy\u2019 in China | Church conversions trend in Australia", "tags": "asia", "timestamp": "2024-08-22", "content": "Dear ST reader,\nWe hope you\u2019ve been keeping well.\nAsia\u2019s leaders remained in the limelight this past week, with Thailand appointing its youngest prime minister in the form of 37-year-old Paetongtarn Shinawatra while elder statesmen from Vietnam, Malaysia and Indonesia visited neighbouring countries to strengthen ties.\nOn his first trip abroad since being elected Vietnam\u2019s president, Mr To Lam made a beeline for Beijing, where he and President Xi Jinping pledged to deepen bilateral relations. Analysts tell our correspondent Lim Min Zhang that Mr Lam is set to continue Vietnam\u2019s \u201cbamboo diplomacy\u201d of being firm but flexible in its dealings with major powers.\nMeanwhile,Malaysia and India elevated their ties to a comprehensive strategic partnership, following talks between their respective prime ministers Anwar Ibrahim and Narendra Modi in New Delhi.\nOver in Canberra, Australia and Indonesia unveiled a landmark defence pact during the visit of Indonesian Defence Minister and President-elect Prabowo Subianto.\nFurther afield, all eyes are on the trilateral partnership between the US, Japan and South Korea, not least because both President Joe Biden and Prime Minister Fumio Kishida are set to step down later this year. Still, analysts assure our correspondent Wendy Teo that the alliance will stay intact because the countries share deep interests beyond defence and security."}